The function defined by
\[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
x + k & \text{if $x < 4$}, \\
2x - 3 & \text{if $x \ge 4$}
\end{array}
\right.\]has an inverse, and the inverse is defined for all real numbers.  Enter all possible values of $k,$ separated by commas.

inference:
For the inverse to be defined for all real numbers, the function must be one-to-one.  This means the graph of $y = f(x)$ must pass the horizontal line test.

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

real func (real x) {
  if (x < 4) {
    return(x + 1);
  }
  else {
    return(2*x - 3);
  }
}

draw(graph(func,-2,3.8),red);
draw(graph(func,4,6),red);
draw((-2,0)--(6,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,10));

label("$y = x + 1$", (3.8,func(3.8)), E, red);
label("$y = 2x - 3$", (5,func(5)), E, red);
[/asy]

The graph of $y = x + k$ is a line with slope 1, and the graph of $y = 2x - 3$ is a line with slope 2.  The two lines must intersect at $x = 4,$ so
\[4 + k = 2 \cdot 4 - 3.\]Solving, we find $k = \boxed{1}.$

ground_truth:
Note that $f(4) = 5.$  If we set $k$ so that $x + 4 = 5,$ then $k = 1.$  This value of $k$ makes the function continuous, as shown below.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

int i;

for (i = -8; i <= 8; ++i) {
  draw((i,-8)--(i,8),gray(0.7));
  draw((-8,i)--(8,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw((-8,0)--(8,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8),Arrows(6));

label("$x$", (8,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,8), N);

draw((4,5)--(11/2,8),red);
draw((-8,-7)--(4,5),red);
dot((4,5),red);
[/asy]

If $k > 1,$ then the function no longer has an inverse since it fails the horizontal line test.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

int i;

for (i = -8; i <= 8; ++i) {
  draw((i,-8)--(i,8),gray(0.7));
  draw((-8,i)--(8,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw((-8,0)--(8,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8),Arrows(6));

label("$x$", (8,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,8), N);

draw((4,5)--(11/2,8),red);
draw((-8,-6)--(4,6),red);

dot((4,5),red);
filldraw(Circle((4,6),0.15),white,red);
[/asy]

And if $k < 1,$ then the function has an inverse, but that inverse is not defined for all real numbers.  Specifically, the inverse is not defined on the interval $[k + 4,5).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

int i;

for (i = -8; i <= 8; ++i) {
  draw((i,-8)--(i,8),gray(0.7));
  draw((-8,i)--(8,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw((-8,0)--(8,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-8)--(0,8),Arrows(6));

label("$x$", (8,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,8), N);

draw((4,5)--(11/2,8),red);
draw((-8,-8)--(4,4),red);

dot((4,5),red);
filldraw(Circle((4,4),0.15),white,red);
[/asy]

Therefore, the only possible value of $k$ is $\boxed{1}.$

